The facial nucleus participates in the corneal reflex 
Corneal pain and temperature fibers go through the ophthalmic division of the fifth cranial nerve to the spinal nucleus of the fifth and thence to the ipsilateral seventh nucleus  causing the eyelid to blink 
There are also central connections between the facial nucleus and the nuclei or projection systems of the second  third  fourth  sixth  and eighth cranial nerves 
These connections coordinate movements among the eyelids and eyeballs and set up certain reflexes such as the blink reflex on exposure to strong light or a loud sound 
